[1]
Date: Thu 15 Mar 2007
From: Maria Zampaglione <m.zampaglione@oie.int>

OIE Press release: FAO and OIE send mission to North Korea
-----------------------------------------------
In response to a request from the government of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea, FAO and the World Organisation for Animal
Health (OIE) are sending a mission to investigate the 1st outbreak of
foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] in the country since 1960.
A team of 3 experts from the FAO/OIE Crisis Management Centre will
arrive in North Korea on 17 Mar 2007 for a one-week visit to assess
the situation, evaluate the need for assistance and provide
recommendations on the response to control the disease.
FMD was 1st diagnosed in January 2007 on a farm in Ryongkok, close to
the capital Pyongyang. The Democratic People's Republic of Korea has
started with internationally accepted disease control measures. Cows
and pigs are being culled in the affected area, and movement controls
have been put in place throughout the country.
FMD is a highly contagious and sometimes fatal viral disease of cows,
sheep, goats and other cloven-hoofed animals, causing blisters on the
nose, mouth and hooves. The disease results in severe production
losses in livestock operations. The disease does not pose a threat to
human health.
--
Maria Zampaglione
Head, Communication Unit
OIE
World Organisation for Animal Health
75017 Paris, France
<http://www.oie.int>
<m.zampaglione@oie.int>
